@article{
  title={A paper about love and death},
  abstract={It is a common phenomenon that we do things for our loved ones who have passed away. After Jennie’s partner died, she quit her job and spent almost a year with all of her savings to travel around the world to fulfill his last wish — having his ashes spread across all five oceans. What Jennie did is no doubt driven by her love for her partner, yet cases like this are virtually absent in contemporary discussion on love. If we would go so long to do things for our dead beloved, shouldn’t our theories of love be able to explain why? 
In this paper, I argue that such cases present a unique problem for contemporary theories of love that focus primarily on uncovering the practical reason love gives us as long as we accept the assumption that the dead doesn’t exist. I consider two representatives of this contemporary approach. 
The first, and perhaps the most popular one, is Frankfurt’s, which claims that love consists in the lover’s benevolence towards the beloved where the benevolence consists in promoting the well-being of the beloved for their own sake. But once we accept that the dead does not exist, it would not take a difficult argument for us to accept that they do not have a well-being either. If this is the case, then the Frankfurtian account has no resources to explain Jennie’s case. 
The Frankfurtian might want to appeal to arguments for the possibility of posthumous harm to salvage their proposal. The idea might be that, if we accept the possibility of posthumous harm, then we may be able to establish that they have a well-being, or, at least, that whatever we do for our dead beloved could be construed as preventing harm happening to them. But I argue that this attempt fails, because the explanation that the benevolence theorist offers for posthumous harm is not satisfactory either. 
Another account of this approach is from Kyla Ebels-Duggan, who argues that love consists in sharing with the beloved their ends. This account faces a similar difficulty as the Frankfurtian account in explaining what Jennie did. If her partner is no longer there, with whom could Jennie share the ends? 
I argue that it is because these accounts focus primarily on the things that we do for and with the beloved that they are at a loss to explain why we do what we do when the beloved passes away. I argue that consideration of the case of loving the dead reveals a non-practical aspect of love that these accounts neglect. I propose that part of what loving someone consists in is taking a particular stance towards them, where taking such a stance consists in, among others, taking pride in what the beloved is proud of, being ashamed of the shameful things that they did, or regret matters that is regrettable for them. Therefore, it is not because we want to promote the well-being of our dead beloved or protect them from harm but because we act from a stance that we share with them. 
}
